  <h2 id="why-diagonal">Why Screen Sizes Are Measured Diagonally</h2>
  <p>Screen sizes are always quoted as a single diagonal measurement: a 24-inch monitor, a 6.1-inch phone, a 55-inch TV. This convention dates back to the early days of television when cathode ray tubes (CRTs) were measured by the diameter of their circular face. Even though modern rectangular screens look very different, the diagonal measurement stuck as the industry standard.</p>
  <p>The diagonal is the single number that best represents a screen's overall size. A 24-inch monitor has more screen area than a 22-inch monitor, regardless of the aspect ratio. The diagonal measurement is also unambiguous &mdash; it is the same whether you are looking at a 16:9 widescreen display or a 4:3 square-ish monitor. Width alone would be misleading because a wide 21:9 ultra-wide monitor would appear to be a much larger screen than a 16:9 monitor with the same diagonal.</p>
  <p>To calculate the diagonal from width and height, use the Pythagorean theorem: diagonal = &radic;(width&sup2; + height&sup2;). For a 16:9 aspect ratio display with a 20.9-inch width and 11.8-inch height: diagonal = &radic;(20.9&sup2; + 11.8&sup2;) = &radic;(436.8 + 139.2) = &radic;576 = 24 inches.</p>

  <h2 id="measure-monitor">How to Measure a Monitor Screen Size</h2>
  <p>Measuring a monitor screen size is straightforward. You need a tape measure or RulerKit's online ruler.</p>
  <p><strong>With a tape measure:</strong> Measure from the top-left corner of the actual display area (not the bezel) to the bottom-right corner. Only measure the glass area where pixels are visible. Do not include the plastic or metal frame around the screen. The result in inches is your monitor's advertised size. A 24-inch monitor will measure approximately 24 inches diagonally.</p>
  <p><strong>With RulerKit's online ruler:</strong> Place your monitor's edge against the screen &mdash; which is a bit tricky for a monitor since you are using the monitor itself. Instead, use the calibration methods. If your monitor has auto-detect, RulerKit reads the EDID data and automatically knows the diagonal. If not, look up your monitor model's specifications on the manufacturer's website.</p>
  <p><strong>Check your operating system:</strong> On Windows, open Settings &gt; System &gt; Display &gt; Advanced display. The monitor name is listed. Search for that model online to find the diagonal size. On macOS, open System Settings &gt; Displays and look for the display name, then look up the specs.</p>

  <h2 id="measure-laptop">How to Measure a Laptop Screen Size</h2>
  <p>Laptop screens are measured the same way as monitors: diagonally from one corner of the display area to the opposite corner. The difference is that laptop screens are typically measured with the lid closed or open depending on how you access the display.</p>
  <p><strong>Method 1: Measure physically.</strong> Open the laptop fully. Use a tape measure from the top-left corner of the display (where pixels begin) to the bottom-right corner. Common laptop sizes include 13.3 inches, 14.0 inches, 15.6 inches, and 17.3 inches. These numbers represent the diagonal of the viewable pixel area, not the lid size.</p>
  <p><strong>Method 2: Check the model specs.</strong> Flip your laptop over and look for the model number sticker. It is usually a string like "XPS 15 9530" or "ThinkPad T14 Gen 3." Search this model number online to find the exact screen size. Most manufacturers list display size prominently in the specifications.</p>
  <p><strong>Method 3: Use RulerKit.</strong> Calibrate the online ruler to your laptop's built-in display using auto-detect or the diagonal calibration method. If you know your laptop's screen size (for example, 15.6 inches), enter that into the calibration panel to verify.</p>
  <p>Laptop screens are sometimes measured differently by manufacturers. A 15.6-inch laptop may actually have a 15.5-inch viewable area depending on how the bezel overlaps the display panel. The difference is usually within 0.1-0.2 inches.</p>

  <h2 id="measure-phone">How to Measure a Phone Screen Size</h2>
  <p>Phone screen sizes are measured diagonally from one corner of the display to the opposite corner. This is the number you see in phone specifications: iPhone 15 Pro Max has a 6.7-inch display, Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra has a 6.8-inch display.</p>
  <p><strong>Physical measurement:</strong> Use a small ruler or tape measure to measure diagonally from the top-left corner of the glass to the bottom-right corner. Only measure the display area, not the bezel or the phone body. For phones with rounded corners, measure to the theoretical corner where the straight edges would meet.</p>
  <p><strong>Software method:</strong> On most phones, you can find the screen size in Settings. On iPhone, go to Settings &gt; General &gt; About and look for the model name. Search that model online for the display size. On Android, go to Settings &gt; About Phone and look for the display specifications.</p>
  <p><strong>Using RulerKit on your phone:</strong> Open RulerKit in your phone's browser. Calibrate using the credit card method or auto-detect. Then switch to inch mode and measure your phone's diagonal by aligning the ruler with the corners of the display. Note that phone measurements on a phone screen can be challenging due to the small screen size and parallax issues.</p>

  <h2 id="measure-tablet">How to Measure a Tablet Screen Size</h2>
  <p>Tablets follow the same diagonal measurement convention. Common tablet sizes include 8.3 inches (iPad Mini), 10.9 inches (iPad Air), 11 inches (iPad Pro), and 12.9 inches (iPad Pro 12.9). Android tablets typically range from 8 to 14 inches.</p>
  <p><strong>Physical measurement:</strong> Lay the tablet flat on a table. Measure diagonally from the top-left corner of the display to the bottom-right corner. Do not include the bezel. The bezel on tablets is often wider than on phones, making it easier to accidentally include it in your measurement. The display area is the part that lights up.</p>
  <p><strong>From specifications:</strong> Tablets have their screen size listed in the product name or specifications. An "iPad Air 11-inch" has an 11-inch display. A "Samsung Galaxy Tab S9 FE" comes in 10.9-inch and 12.4-inch versions. Always verify against the model number if you are unsure which version you have.</p>

  <h2 id="measure-tv">How to Measure a TV Screen Size</h2>
  <p>TVs are the most common application of diagonal screen measurement. A 55-inch TV measures 55 inches diagonally. Unlike monitors and laptops, TVs are almost always measured by their advertised diagonal, and the measurement includes the entire display panel (the glass area), not just the bezel-less viewable area.</p>
  <p><strong>With a tape measure:</strong> Measure from the top-left corner of the glass panel to the bottom-right corner. For large TVs, you may need a long tape measure or an assistant. Most TV sizes range from 32 inches to 85 inches, with 55, 65, and 75 inches being the most popular sizes.</p>
  <p><strong>Without a tape measure:</strong> If your TV is mounted or hard to reach, look up the model number on the back of the TV or in the settings menu. Search that number online. The screen size is always listed in the specifications. You can also measure the width of the TV and calculate the diagonal using the aspect ratio. A 55-inch 16:9 TV is approximately 47.9 inches wide.</p>
  <p>TV sizes can be confusing because the advertised size may be slightly different from the actual viewable area. Most modern TVs list the viewable diagonal, which is the industry standard. If you are building a cabinet or entertainment center, always check the TV's physical dimensions (width, height, depth with stand) rather than relying solely on the diagonal screen size.</p>

  <h2 id="aspect-ratio">Understanding Aspect Ratio and Diagonal</h2>
  <p>Aspect ratio describes the proportional relationship between a screen's width and height. The most common aspect ratios are 16:9 (widescreen, used by most TVs and monitors), 16:10 (used by some productivity monitors and laptops), 21:9 (ultra-wide monitors), 4:3 (older monitors and tablets), and 19.5:9 or similar (modern smartphones).</p>
  <p>The aspect ratio matters because two screens with the same diagonal can have very different widths and heights. A 24-inch 16:9 monitor is 20.9 inches wide and 11.8 inches tall. A 24-inch 4:3 monitor (if one existed) would be 19.2 inches wide and 14.4 inches tall. They have the same diagonal but very different screen areas: the 4:3 screen has about 19% more actual display area.</p>
  <p>When measuring your screen size for a specific application &mdash; like fitting a monitor into a desk setup or buying a screen protector &mdash; you need both the diagonal size and the aspect ratio. RulerKit uses both when you calibrate via the screen diagonal method, ensuring the width and height are calculated correctly.</p>

