  <h2 id="online-vs-tape">Online Tools vs. a Tape Measure</h2>
  <p>Both methods for measuring screen size have their place. Here is when to use each.</p>
  <h3>When to use an online tool</h3>
  <p>RulerKit's online ruler is ideal when you do not have a tape measure handy, when the screen is mounted or difficult to access (like a wall-mounted TV), or when you want to verify the manufacturer's specifications. Online tools are also useful for measuring multiple screens quickly &mdash; for example, checking the screen sizes of several laptops before making a purchase decision. The auto-detect feature makes it especially convenient for modern monitors and laptops.</p>
  <h3>When to use a physical tape measure</h3>
  <p>A physical tape measure is more accurate and does not require calibration. If you need a precise measurement for fitting a screen into a tight space (like a monitor into a shelf cubby or a TV into an entertainment center), use a tape measure. Physical measurement also works for any screen regardless of age, model, or connectivity. For older monitors that do not support EDID auto-detection, a tape measure is the most reliable method.</p>
  <p>The best approach is to use both methods for cross-verification. Measure with RulerKit first for speed, then confirm with a tape measure for critical installations.</p>

  <h2 id="viewable-area">Viewable Area vs. Bezel</h2>
  <p>The "screen size" you see advertised always refers to the viewable display area, not the total physical size including the bezel. The bezel is the frame around the display &mdash; the plastic, metal, or glass border that does not show pixels.</p>
  <p>On modern devices, bezels vary widely. A typical monitor has a bezel of 5-15 mm on each side. Some premium monitors advertise "zero-bezel" designs where the bezel is only 2-3 mm thick. Laptops have bezels that range from 5 mm (Dell XPS series) to 15 mm or more (budget laptops). The advertised screen size is the diagonal of the pixel area, not the diagonal of the outer lid or case.</p>
  <p>When measuring screen size yourself, be careful to measure only the glass area where pixels are visible. On some devices, there is a black border between the visible pixels and the outer bezel. This black border is not part of the viewable area. Start your tape measure where the first pixel is visible, not at the edge of the glass panel.</p>

  <h2 id="find-model-specs">Finding Your Model Specs Online</h2>
  <p>If you cannot measure your screen directly, the next best option is to look up your device's specifications. Here is how to find the model number and look up the screen size.</p>
  <p><strong>Monitors:</strong> The model number is usually printed on a sticker on the back of the monitor. It may also appear in the on-screen display menu. Search "MonitorName specs" on Google or check the manufacturer's support page. The screen size is always listed in the display specifications.</p>
  <p><strong>Laptops:</strong> Flip the laptop over and look for the model number sticker near the hinge. On Windows, the model is shown in System Information. On macOS, click the Apple logo &gt; About This Mac &gt; System Report. Search the model number online for the display specifications.</p>
  <p><strong>Phones:</strong> On iPhone, go to Settings &gt; General &gt; About. The model name is listed. On Android, go to Settings &gt; About Phone. The model number is usually something like SM-S921U (Samsung) or Pixel 8 Pro (Google). Search for "PhoneName display size" for the diagonal measurement.</p>
  <p><strong>Tablets:</strong> Model information is typically in Settings &gt; About Tablet. The screen size is often part of the product name (e.g., "iPad Pro 12.9-inch"). If not, the model number lookup will reveal the display size.</p>
  <p><strong>TVs:</strong> The model number is on a sticker on the back or side of the TV. It may also be found in the settings menu under Support &gt; Contact Support or About. TV model numbers often encode the screen size: a Sony XR-55A80L is a 55-inch TV. Look for the two-digit number near the beginning or end of the model string.</p>

  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq space-y-4 not-prose">
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Why are screens measured diagonally instead of by width?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">The diagonal measurement is a convention inherited from early CRT televisions, which had circular screens measured by diameter. The diagonal stuck because it is a single number that reasonably represents the overall size of a rectangular display, and it works across different aspect ratios. Width alone would make wide 21:9 screens appear larger than they really are.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">How can I measure screen size without a ruler or tape measure?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Use RulerKit's online ruler on a calibrated screen, or look up your device model number online. You can also use known objects for reference. For example, a standard credit card is 3.37 inches wide. Measure how many card-widths fit across your screen and multiply to estimate the size.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Does aspect ratio affect the screen size measurement?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">The diagonal measurement itself is not affected by aspect ratio. A 24-inch screen is always 24 inches diagonally. However, the width and height depend on the aspect ratio. Two screens with the same diagonal but different aspect ratios will have different dimensions and different total screen areas.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Is a TV screen measured the same way as a monitor screen?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Yes. Both TVs and monitors are measured diagonally from corner to corner of the viewable display area. The measurement does not include the bezel on either type of device. The same diagonal measurement standard applies to phones, tablets, laptops, and all other screen-based devices.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">What is the difference between screen size and viewable area?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Screen size and viewable area are the same thing for modern displays. Both refer to the diagonal measurement of the pixel area. The confusion arises with the physical dimensions including the bezel. A 24-inch monitor may be 22 inches wide including the bezel, but the advertised 24 inches is the diagonal of the pixels only.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Can I use RulerKit to measure my TV screen size?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Not directly, because you would need to place the TV against your computer screen. Instead, use RulerKit to calibrate your computer's display, then use a known-size reference to estimate the TV size. For accurate TV measurements, use a tape measure or look up the model number online.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
